## 2. C++ side – the *binding glue*

Below is a **single `.cpp` file** that contains:

1. A tiny stub of the `libpcapng` public API (you will replace the stub with the real headers / implementation).  
2. The pybind11 binding code exposing the API described above.  
3. All necessary GIL handling, error translation and documentation strings.

> **NOTE** – If you already have the real `libpcapng` headers, just `#include` them and delete the stub section.

```cpp
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// file: libpcapng_binding.cpp
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
#define PY_SSIZE_T_CLEAN
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>          // for std::vector -> list conversion
#include <pybind11/functional.h>   // for std::function <-> Python callable
#include <pybind11/iostream.h>     // optional: redirect C++ i/o to Python

namespace py = pybind11;

// ----------------------------------------------------------------
// 1️⃣  STUB of the libpcapng public API (replace with real includes)
// ----------------------------------------------------------------
namespace libpcapng {
    using timestamp_t = uint64_t; // nanoseconds since epoch (example)

    struct Frame {
        uint64_t number;          // 1‑based index
        timestamp_t timestamp;    // nanoseconds
        uint32_t captured_len;    // bytes stored in file
        uint32_t original_len;    // bytes on the wire
        std::vector<uint8_t> data; // raw bytes

        // convenience for Python repr
        std::string to_string() const {
            char buf[128];
            std::snprintf(buf, sizeof(buf),
                "Frame #%llu ts=%llu captured=%u original=%u",
                (unsigned long long)number,
                (unsigned long long)timestamp,
                captured_len,
                original_len);
            return std::string(buf);
        }
    };

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // The iterator that libpcapng provides (very simplified)
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    class FrameIterator {
    public:
        // Construct from a filename (or any other source you have)
        explicit FrameIterator(const std::string& path) : m_path(path) {
            // In real code: open file, parse header, etc.
            // For the stub we just simulate a finite sequence.
            m_current = 0;
            m_total   = 500; // pretend we have 500 frames
        }

        // Return true if another frame is available
        bool has_next() const { return m_current < m_total; }

        // Advance and return the next frame (throws if none)
        Frame next() {
            if (!has_next())
                throw std::out_of_range("End of iterator");

            // Simulate some data
            Frame f;
            f.number = ++m_current;
            f.timestamp = 1'600'000'000'000'000ULL + f.number * 1'000'000ULL; // 1‑ms steps
            f.captured_len = 64 + (f.number % 64);
            f.original_len = f.captured_len;
            f.data.resize(f.captured_len, static_cast<uint8_t>(f.number & 0xFF));
            return f;
        }

    private:
        std::string m_path;
        uint64_t    m_current;
        uint64_t    m_total;
    };

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // A "reader" object that owns the iterator – this is what we expose.
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    class PcapngReader {
    public:
        explicit PcapngReader(const std::string& path)
            : m_iter(path) {}

        // Python iterator protocol (makes the object itself iterable)
        bool   py_has_next() const { return m_iter.has_next(); }
        Frame  py_next()          { return m_iter.next(); }

        // The "walk with callback" API
        template <typename Callable>
        void walk(Callable&& cb) {
            // Release the GIL while we do the heavy C++ loop.
            // The GIL will be reacquired for each callback invocation.
            py::gil_scoped_release release;
            while (m_iter.has_next()) {
                Frame f = m_iter.next();
                // Re‑acquire GIL for the Python call.
                py::gil_scoped_acquire acquire;
                // Propagate StopIteration as a signal to abort early.
                try {
                    cb(f);
                } catch (py::stop_iteration&) {
                    // user asked to stop – break out of the C++ loop.
                    break;
                }
                // The GIL will be released again at the end of the loop
                // iteration (when `acquire` goes out of scope).
            }
        }

    private:
        FrameIterator m_iter;
    };
} // namespace libpcapng

// ----------------------------------------------------------------
// 2️⃣  pybind11 binding code
// ----------------------------------------------------------------
PYBIND11_MODULE(libpcapng, m) {
    m.doc() = R"pbdoc(
        Python bindings for libpcapng – a simple iterator over captured frames.

        The most common entry point is :class:`PcapngReader`, which can be used
        either as a normal Python iterator::

            for frame in libpcapng.PcapngReader("file.pcapng"):
                ...

        or with a callback via :meth:`PcapngReader.for_each`::

            def my_cb(frame):
                ...

            libpcapng.PcapngReader("file.pcapng").for_each(my_cb)

        The :class:`Frame` object exposes a few useful fields.
    )pbdoc";

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // Frame
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    py::class_<libpcapng::Frame>(m, "Frame", R"pbdoc(
        A single captured frame.

        Attributes
        ----------
        number : int
            1‑based index of the frame in the file.
        timestamp : int
            Nanoseconds since the Unix epoch.
        captured_len : int
            Number of bytes stored in the capture file.
        original_len : int
            Number of bytes on the wire (may be larger than ``captured_len``).
        data : bytes
            Raw payload bytes.
    )pbdoc")
        .def_readonly("number",        &libpcapng::Frame::number)
        .def_readonly("timestamp",     &libpcapng::Frame::timestamp)
        .def_readonly("captured_len",  &libpcapng::Frame::captured_len)
        .def_readonly("original_len",  &libpcapng::Frame::original_len)
        .def_property_readonly(
            "data",
            [](const libpcapng::Frame& self) -> py::bytes {
                // Convert std::vector<uint8_t> → Python bytes object
                return py::bytes(reinterpret_cast<const char*>(self.data.data()),
                                 self.data.size());
            },
            "Raw packet bytes"
        )
        .def("__repr__", [](const libpcapng::Frame& self) {
            return "<libpcapng.Frame " + self.to_string() + ">";
        });

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // PcapngReader – the main entry point
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    py::class_<libpcapng::PcapngReader>(m, "PcapngReader", R"pbdoc(
        Open a pcapng file and iterate over its frames.

        Parameters
        ----------
        path : str
            Path to a pcapng file (or any other source supported by libpcapng).

        Notes
        -----
        The reader object is *iterable* – you can use ``for frame in reader``.
        It also provides :meth:`for_each` for a callback‑driven walk.
    )pbdoc")
        .def(py::init<const std::string&>(),
             py::arg("path"),
             "Create a new reader for *path*.")
        // ---- Python iterator protocol (makes the object itself iterable) ----
        .def("__iter__", [](libpcapng::PcapngReader& self) -> libpcapng::PcapngReader& {
            return self;
        }, py::keep_alive<0, 1>())   // keep reader alive while iterator lives
        .def("__next__", [](libpcapng::PcapngReader& self) -> libpcapng::Frame {
            if (!self.py_has_next())
                throw py::stop_iteration();
            return self.py_next();
        })
        // ---- Callback‑driven walk ------------------------------------------------
        .def("for_each",
             [](libpcapng::PcapngReader& self, py::function py_cb) {
                 // The template ``walk`` method expects any callable.
                 // We forward the Python function (which is a py::function) –
                 // pybind11 will automatically convert the C++ Frame argument to
                 // a Python Frame object.
                 self.walk(py_cb);
             },
             py::arg("callback"),
             R"pbdoc(
                Walk the capture and invoke *callback* for each frame.

                The *callback* receives a single argument – a :class:`Frame` object.
                If the callback raises :class:`StopIteration`, the walk aborts
                early. Any other Python exception propagates as a
                :class:`RuntimeError`.

                The iteration is performed in C++ (the GIL is released while
                reading the file) and the GIL is reacquired only for the
                callback, so the walk is efficient even for very large files.
            )pbdoc")
        // ---- Utility: expose the number of frames (optional) ------------
        .def_property_readonly(
            "estimated_frame_count",
            [](const libpcapng::PcapngReader& self) -> size_t {
                // In a real implementation you could expose a fast count here.
                // For the stub we just return a dummy value.
                return 500;
            },
            "Rough estimate of total frames (may be inaccurate)."
        );

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // Translate C++ std::exception to Python RuntimeError (optional)
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    py::register_exception<std::runtime_error>(m, "RuntimeError");
    py::register_exception<std::out_of_range>(m, "StopIteration");
}
```

### Explanation of the binding design

| Feature | How it is implemented |
|---------|-----------------------|
| **Iterating with `for frame in reader`** | The class implements `__iter__` returning itself and `__next__` that forwards to the native iterator (`py_has_next` / `py_next`). The `StopIteration` exception is raised automatically when the native iterator reports EOF. |
| **Callback walk (`for_each`)** | The method receives a `py::function`. Inside `PcapngReader::walk` we **release the GIL** for the whole C++ loop (`py::gil_scoped_release`). For each frame we **re‑acquire** the GIL (`py::gil_scoped_acquire`) just before invoking the Python callable. This gives you the performance of a pure C++ scan while still allowing arbitrary Python code per frame. |
| **Early abort** | If the Python callback raises `StopIteration`, we catch it in the C++ loop and break out. Any other Python exception propagates out of `for_each` as a Python `RuntimeError`. |
| **Zero‑copy frame data** | The stub copies the raw bytes into a `std::vector<uint8_t>`. In a real libpcapng build you can either keep that copy (simple) or expose a read‑only memory view (`py::memoryview`) that points directly into the libpcapng buffer. The example uses `py::bytes` for simplicity. |
| **Reference‑lifetime handling** | `py::keep_alive<0, 1>()` on `__iter__` guarantees the `PcapngReader` stays alive as long as the iterator (i.e. the Python loop) is in use. The `Frame` objects are independent copies, so they survive after the iterator finishes. |
| **Error translation** | `std::out_of_range` from the underlying iterator is turned into a Python `StopIteration` (so the iterator protocol works). Other `std::runtime_error`s become generic `RuntimeError`s. |
| **Documentation** | Docstrings are embedded directly in the binding source (`R"pbdoc(...)"pbdoc`). When the module is imported, `help(libpcapng.PcapngReader)` will show them. |
| **Thread‑safety** | The GIL is only held while calling the user callback. The heavy C++ walk can run in a background thread (just call `for_each` from a thread) – the GIL handling ensures no race with the interpreter. |

